First, we sketch each of the three curves to see what is the region that
we are talking about.

\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{../json_data/MATH105/April_2010/MER_MATH105_April_2010_3.png}

We will need to find the coordinates of points \emph{A} and \emph{B}
which are the intersection of curves. For \emph{A} we have

\begin{align*}
-x &= - \frac{2}{x}\\
x^2 &= 2\\
x &= \pm \sqrt{2}
\end{align*} We can see from the picture that we are interested in the
point with a positive \emph{x} coordinate, so

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
A = (\sqrt{2}, -\sqrt{2})
\end{align*}

For \emph{B} we have

\begin{align*}
-4\sqrt{x} &= - \frac{2}{x}\\
x^{3/2} &= \frac{1}{2}\\
x &= \left( \frac{1}{2} \right)^{2/3} = \frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{4}}
\end{align*} And so since \emph{y} = -2/\emph{x} we have

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
B = \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{4}}, -2\sqrt[3]{4} \right)
\end{align*}

This allows us to write the desired area as the sum of 2 integrals

\begin{align*}
\text{area} &= \int_0^{\frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{4}}} \left( (-x) - (-4\sqrt{x}) \right) \,dx + \int_{\frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{4}}}^{\sqrt{2}} \left( (-x) - (-\frac{2}{x}) \right) \,dx\\
&= \int_0^{\frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{4}}} \left( -x+4\sqrt {x} \right) \,dx + \int_{\frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{4}}}^{\sqrt{2}} \left( -x + \frac{2}{x} \right) \,dx\\
&= \left[ -\frac{x^2}{2} + \frac{4\cdot 2}{3} x^{3/2} \right]_0^{\frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{4}}} + \left[ -\frac{x^2}{2} + 2\ln(x) \right]_{\frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{4}}}^{\sqrt{2}}\\
&= -\frac{(2^{-2/3})^2}{2} + \frac{8}{3} (2^{-2/3})^{3/2} + 0 - 0 - \frac{(\sqrt{2})^2}{2} + 2\ln(\sqrt{2}) + \frac{(2^{-2/3})^2}{2} - 2\ln(2^{-2/3})\\
&= \frac{4}{3} - 1 +\ln(2) + \frac{4}{3}\ln(2)\\
&=\frac{1}{3}+\frac{7}{3}\ln(2)
\end{align*}

